titleproper.value:
Guide to the Edwin Rolfe Photograph Collection
                    <num>ALBA.PHOTO.010</num>

author.value: Finding aid prepared by Evan Daniel, 2004

creation.value:
This finding aid was produced using the Archivists' Toolkit
                <date>2012-03-29T14:14-0400</date>

abstract.label: Abstract
abstract.value:
Edwin Rolfe - born Solomon Fishman - (1910-1954) was a journalist, author, and Communist Party activist. In 1937, Rolfe went to Spain to cover the Spanish Civil War for the 
                <title render="italic">Volunteer for Liberty</title>and the 
                <title render="italic">Daily Worker</title>. The images in this collection were accrued by Rolfe in the course of his work as a journalist in Spain. The collection contains images of British author and assistant commissar of the Fifteenth International Brigade Ralph Bates and African-American author Langston Hughes as well as barricades, bombed/shelled buildings, medical personnel and street scenes

p.value:
Published citations should take the following form: 
                <lb/>
                <lb/>Identification of item, date; Collection name; Collection number; box number; folder number; 
                <lb/>Tamiment Library/Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives 
                <lb/>Elmer Holmes Bobst Library 
                <lb/>70 Washington Square South 
                <lb/>New York, NY 10012, New York University Libraries.

Rolfe accrued the images in this collection in the course of his work as a journalist for the 
                <title render="italic">Volunteer for Liberty</title>and the 
                <title render="italic">Daily Worker</title>.

The photographic prints are identified by four numbers separated by colons. The first number refers to the collection number, the second to the box number, the third to the folder number, and the fourth to the individual print. For example, the first print in this collection is labeled 10:1:1:1. Negatives are numbered in the same fashion and if there is a matching print, the print number is listed below the negative number. If a print does not have a negative, the print sleeve reads “no negative” or “no neg.”
